{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"33fc4340-4f23-456c-a564-fee1f0eef894","content":"The .NET MAUI Android build system **ignores `JAVA_HOME`**. It uses its own JDK resolution via the MSBuild property `JavaSdkDirectory`, which defaults to the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the Android workload.\n\nYour Adoptium JDK works fine for `java -version`, but MSBuild never sees it.\n\n**Fix — pick one:**\n\n1. **Install the workload-bundled JDK** (recommended):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet workload repair\n   ```\n   This ensures the Microsoft OpenJDK expected by the build is in place.\n\n2. **Point MSBuild to your Adoptium JDK** — add to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n     <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\nOption 1 is preferred since it keeps everything aligned with what the workload expects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"348a979a-0f51-4573-8ba4-5766ccb37274","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about common .NET MAUI Android + Java issues:\n\n1. .NET MAUI Android builds require a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI/Android workloads ship with their own JDK (Microsoft OpenJDK 17), and the build system looks for it in a specific location.\n\n2. A very common issue is that even though JAVA_HOME is set, the .NET Android build tooling may not respect JAVA_HOME and instead looks for the JDK bundled with the Android workload (typically Microsoft's OpenJDK distribution installed via the Android workload).\n\n\n3. The build system actually uses `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` which defaults to the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the workload rather than respecting JAVA_HOME, even though the user has JDK 17.0.12 installed. There's a known macOS-specific issue with Adoptium Temurin that might be causing the problem. The Android workload's bundled JDK might be missing or corrupted, preventing MSBuild from finding it even if JAVA_HOME is set. But there's another angle—.NET 9 MAUI actually requires JDK 21, not JDK 17, so if the user is on a newer .NET version with an older JDK, that would explain the failure. Let me think about what the most likely culprit is here given the timeline. fail because it doesn't look at JAVA_HOME by default. The real fix is either setting `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` in the project file to point to Adoptium, or installing the Microsoft OpenJDK that comes with the workload. Actually, the most common issue on macOS is that JAVA_HOME needs to be set to the full path including `Contents/Home` — if it's missing that suffix, the build tools won't find the JDK properly.\n\nBut since the user confirmed `java -version` works, their PATH is fine. The actual problem is that .NET MAUI's Android build doesn't use `JAVA_HOME` at all — it relies on its own JDK resolution through the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property, which by default looks for Microsoft's OpenJDK from the workload, not the system JAVA_HOME. The solution is either installing the proper workload with `dotnet workload install maui-android` or manually setting `JavaSdkDirectory` to point to the Adoptium installation.","outputTokens":1803,"requestId":"0432:286828:AB8F35:C43670:6A0279A8"},"id":"94fad982-7e6c-4e05-9b5f-f3ffd238ff7a","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:52:30.525Z","parentId":"e1e0782d-7037-428c-a5a6-c11bc3db9ed4"}
